---
import BlogPost from "../../layouts/BlogPost.astro";
import StatRow from "../../components/blog/StatRow.astro";
import Callout from "../../components/blog/Callout.astro";
import Timeline from "../../components/blog/Timeline.astro";
import Flow from "../../components/blog/Flow.astro";
import DiffBlock from "../../components/blog/DiffBlock.astro";
import Lesson from "../../components/blog/Lesson.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../components/blog/CodeBlock.astro";
import { posts } from "../../data/posts";

const post = posts.find((p) => p.slug === "openclaw-pr84890-postmortem")!;
const loc = post.en;
---

<BlogPost
  lang="en"
  slug={post.slug}
  title={loc.title}
  description={loc.description}
  tag={loc.tag}
  date={post.date}
  meta={[
    { text: "myps6415" },
    {
      text: "PR #84890 · openclaw/openclaw",
      href: "https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/84890",
    },
  ]}
>
  <StatRow
    stats={[
      { value: "374k", label: "GitHub Stars" },
      { value: "+29/-1", label: "Diff size" },
      { value: "P1", label: "Issue priority" },
    ]}
  />

  <h2>Background</h2>

  <p>
    OpenClaw is a 374k-star open source AI assistant framework. I use it
    day-to-day in my homelab to run a Telegram bot. Its gateway is a Node.js
    process running under macOS launchd, exposing a REST API that various
    agents call.
  </p>

  <p>
    One day I clicked the Update button in the control panel. The update
    reported <code>status=ok</code> and everything looked normal. A few hours
    later I noticed the gateway throwing errors:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock label="production log · PID 30106">
{`13:35:15  request handler failed: ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND
          task-registry.maintenance-B-jsfe-3.js
13:36:55  ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND  status.link-channel-BK3OG460.js
14:16:52  ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND  task-registry.maintenance-B-jsfe-3.js
14:16:54  [restart] request coalesced (already in-flight) reason=update.run
14:31:31  ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND  hooks-DBKknpfW.js`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <p>
    The stranger part: the last entry in <code>gateway-restart.log</code> was
    six days old. The gateway was running, but would never restart. The only
    workaround was to manually run <code
      >launchctl kickstart -k gui/$(id -u)/ai.openclaw.gateway</code
    >.
  </p>

  <h2>Root cause</h2>

  <p>
    Reading the source, I traced it to a chicken-and-egg deadlock caused by
    three independent design choices stacking together.
  </p>

  <h3>Problem 1: the SIGUSR1 listener uses dynamic import</h3>

  <CodeBlock label="src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.ts (before)" lang="typescript">
{`const onSigusr1 = () => {
  gatewayLog.info("signal SIGUSR1 received");
  void (async () => {
    const {
      markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled,
      ...
    } = await loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule();  // ← dynamic import
    request("restart", "SIGUSR1", restartReason);
    markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled();              // ← never called
  })();
  // Note: no .catch() here
};`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <h3>Problem 2: chunk hashes rotate after an upgrade</h3>

  <p>
    After <code>npm install -g openclaw@newer</code> swaps the package, the
    chunk filenames in <code>dist/</code> (each suffixed with a content hash)
    are all replaced. The old process is still running, but the paths it
    tries to import no longer exist. Result:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock>
{`loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule()
  → import("./lifecycle.runtime-OLDHASH.js")
  → ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND  ← silent reject, no .catch()`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <h3>Problem 3: the restart token gets stuck</h3>

  <p>
    OpenClaw's restart system uses a pair of counters to prevent duplicate
    triggers:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock label="src/infra/restart.ts" lang="typescript">
{`function hasUnconsumedRestartSignal(): boolean {
  return emittedRestartToken > consumedRestartToken;
}

export function scheduleGatewaySigusr1Restart(opts?) {
  if (hasUnconsumedRestartSignal()) {
    restartLog.warn(\`restart request coalesced (already in-flight)\`);
    return { coalesced: true };  // ← bail out, do nothing
  }
  // ...
}`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <p>
    Because the SIGUSR1 handler rejects at <code
      >await loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule()</code
    >, <code>markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled()</code> — i.e.{" "}
    <code>consumedRestartToken++</code> — is never called.{" "}
    <code>emittedRestartToken</code> stays permanently above{" "}
    <code>consumedRestartToken</code>, and every subsequent restart request
    gets coalesced away.
  </p>

  <Callout variant="err" title="Deadlock structure">
    The SIGUSR1 listener needs to import the lifecycle module to handle a
    restart → but the lifecycle module's chunk has been swapped out → import
    fails → the token is never consumed → every subsequent restart request is
    coalesced → the gateway never restarts.
  </Callout>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>

  <Timeline
    items={[
      {
        time: "2026-05-15",
        text: "Last successful restart",
        sub: "Final valid entry in gateway-restart.log",
        status: "ok",
      },
      {
        time: "2026-05-18 → 05-19",
        text: "Version upgrade triggers the bug",
        sub: "npm install -g openclaw@newer completes; chunk hashes rotate",
        status: "bad",
      },
      {
        time: "14:16:54",
        text: "Gateway enters coalesce loop",
        sub: "[restart] request coalesced (already in-flight) reason=update.run",
        status: "bad",
      },
      {
        time: "Six days running",
        text: "ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND keeps firing",
        sub: "PID 30106 uptime > 36h, process never replaced",
        status: "bad",
      },
      {
        time: "2026-05-21",
        text: "Filed PR #84890",
        sub: "Attached production log + live terminal proof",
        status: "ok",
      },
      {
        time: "2026-05-22",
        text: "PR merged by vincentkoc",
        sub: "+29/-1, single-file change",
        status: "ok",
      },
    ]}
  />

  <h2>The fix</h2>

  <p>
    The core idea is simple: <strong
      >load the lifecycle module into the ESM cache before installing the
      signal listener</strong
    >. After that, every <code>await loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule()</code
    > hits the cache instead of disk, so chunk rotation can't affect it.
  </p>

  <Flow
    steps={[
      {
        marker: "1",
        status: "ok",
        title: "Eager-load: import before installing the signal listener",
        desc: "First line of runGatewayLoop, before acquireGatewayLock",
      },
      {
        marker: "2",
        status: "ok",
        title: "Defence in depth: add .catch() to the SIGUSR1 IIFE",
        desc: "Use the cached reference; guarantee the token is consumed",
      },
      {
        marker: "!",
        status: "warn",
        title: "Fail-fast contract",
        desc: "If the lifecycle module isn't found at startup → fail loudly, let the supervisor handle it, no half-dead process",
      },
    ]}
  />

  <DiffBlock
    header="src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.ts"
    lines={[
      { kind: "hunk", text: "@@ -120,6 +120,9 @@ export async function runGatewayLoop(opts) {" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+  const eagerLifecycleRuntime = await loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule();" },
      { kind: "ctx", text: "   await acquireGatewayLock();" },
      { kind: "ctx", text: "   // ... rest of init ..." },
      { kind: "hunk", text: "@@ -600,8 +603,15 @@ const onSigusr1 = () => {" },
      { kind: "ctx", text: "   void (async () => {" },
      { kind: "ctx", text: "     const { ... } = await loadGatewayLifecycleRuntimeModule();" },
      { kind: "ctx", text: "     request(\"restart\", \"SIGUSR1\", restartReason);" },
      { kind: "del", text: "-    markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled();" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+    eagerLifecycleRuntime.markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled();" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+  }).catch((err) => {" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+    gatewayLog.error(\"SIGUSR1 handler failed\", err);" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+    eagerLifecycleRuntime.markGatewaySigusr1RestartHandled();" },
      { kind: "add", text: "+  });" },
    ]}
  />

  <h2>Alternatives considered</h2>

  <p>I considered three alternatives in the PR before settling on this:</p>

  <Lesson label="Option A">
    Replace SIGUSR1 with <code>process.exit(0)</code> on package swap — too
    aggressive, loses in-process drain, and is an orthogonal concern. It can
    stack on top of this fix but doesn't replace it.
  </Lesson>
  <Lesson label="Option B">
    Make <code>update.run</code> always go through launchd kickstart — treats
    only the symptom. Config watcher, manual SIGUSR1, and other paths still
    hit the same bug.
  </Lesson>
  <Lesson label="Option C">
    Wrap the dynamic import in <code>try/catch</code> inside the listener —
    only fixes one callsite. <code>run-loop.ts</code> has ~10 lifecycle
    dynamic-import callsites; one eager-load fixes them all.
  </Lesson>

  <h2>Verification</h2>

  <p>
    After a local build I triggered the previously-deadlocked path with{" "}
    <code>kill -USR1 &lt;pid&gt;</code>:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock label="terminal output after the patch">
{`$ kill -USR1 47154
$ tail -n 8 /tmp/pr-gw-test.log
2026-05-21T19:52:27.296+08:00 [gateway] signal SIGUSR1 received
2026-05-21T19:52:27.310+08:00 [gateway] received SIGUSR1; restarting
2026-05-21T19:52:27.335+08:00 [shutdown] started: gateway restarting
2026-05-21T19:52:28.274+08:00 [gmail-watcher] gmail watcher stopped
2026-05-21T19:52:28.279+08:00 [shutdown] completed cleanly in 943ms
2026-05-21T19:52:28.285+08:00 [gateway] restart mode: in-process restart`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <p>
    Before: <code>signal SIGUSR1 received</code> appears once, then total
    silence — every restart returns <code>coalesced: true</code>. After: the
    full shutdown sequence runs and exits cleanly in 943ms.
  </p>

  <p>I also ran the five related vitest suites:</p>

  <CodeBlock>
{`$ pnpm exec vitest run src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.test.ts \\
    src/infra/restart.test.ts src/infra/restart-coordinator.test.ts \\
    src/gateway/server-methods/update.test.ts \\
    src/cli/gateway-cli/run.supervised-lock.test.ts

 Test Files  5 passed (5)
      Tests  56 passed (56)`}
  </CodeBlock>

  <h2>Takeaways</h2>

  <Lesson label="On ESM lazy loading">
    Dynamic import inside a signal handler is dangerous. Signal handlers fire
    at unpredictable times, and anything that touches disk can fail if the
    environment has changed underneath it. The recovery path shouldn't depend
    on the thing it's recovering.
  </Lesson>

  <Lesson label="On async IIFE">
    <code>void (async () => &lbrace;...&rbrace;)()</code> without a <code
      >.catch()</code
    > is a quiet time bomb. Particularly dangerous in a signal handler, where
    failure is silent and leaves no observable trace.
  </Lesson>

  <Lesson label="On open source contribution">
    The most convincing PR is "this happened to me in production." A slice of
    production logs plus a live terminal proof beat any unit test. ClawSweeper
    bot's final grade was platinum hermit — the jump from the initial silver
    shellfish came from that terminal screenshot.
  </Lesson>

  <Callout variant="ok" title="AI collaboration">
    This PR was done in collaboration with Claude Code (<code
      >Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7</code
    >). I owned root cause analysis and production verification; Claude Code
    handled implementation details. Diagnosis and verification have to be
    yours — no one knows your production environment better than you.
  </Callout>
</BlogPost>
